2.	Different ways to backup DB?

When interviewers ask about different ways to back up a database, they‚Äôre usually looking for both:

The types of backups (conceptually)

The methods/tools (technically)

Here‚Äôs a clear breakdown you can use in an interview answer:

1. Backup Types
These define what data and how much is captured.

Full Backup ‚Äì Copies the entire database in one go.

Pros: Simple restore.

Cons: Slow, large storage.

Incremental Backup ‚Äì Only backs up data changed since the last backup (full or incremental).

Pros: Saves space & time.

Cons: Restore is slower (need last full + all incrementals).

Differential Backup ‚Äì Backs up data changed since the last full backup.

Pros: Faster restore than incremental.

Cons: Gets larger over time until next full backup.

Transaction Log Backup ‚Äì Captures transaction logs so you can restore to a specific point in time.

Useful for point-in-time recovery.

File/Filegroup Backup ‚Äì Back up specific files or partitions of a large DB (common in very large DBs).

Snapshot ‚Äì Read-only, instantaneous copy of the DB at a given moment (storage-dependent).

2. Backup Methods / Storage Options
These define where/how the backup is stored.

On-disk backups ‚Äì Save to local or network drives.

Cloud backups ‚Äì Use managed services like AWS RDS snapshots, Azure SQL Backup, Google Cloud SQL export.

Export-based backups ‚Äì Export schema/data to SQL dump files (mysqldump, pg_dump).

Logical backups ‚Äì Backup in a logical format (tables, schema definitions, data) ‚Äî portable across DB versions.

Physical backups ‚Äì Copy the actual DB data files (e.g., xtrabackup, Oracle RMAN).

3. Backup Automation & Strategy
Scheduled backups (cron jobs, SQL Agent jobs)

Hot backup ‚Äì Taken while DB is running (requires specific DB support).

Cold backup ‚Äì Taken while DB is offline.

Replication as backup ‚Äì Secondary replica can act as a recovery source.

Archival backups ‚Äì Store older backups to cheaper long-term storage (tape, Glacier).

‚úÖ Example interview answer:

"There are multiple ways to back up a database, which we usually choose based on recovery objectives and storage needs. The main types are full, differential, incremental, and transaction log backups.
For example, we might do a weekly full backup, daily differential, and hourly transaction log backups for point-in-time recovery.
Technically, we can back up by exporting logical data (mysqldump), taking physical copies of data files (e.g., RMAN), using cloud-native snapshot features, or setting up replication as a standby.
We can automate these backups, store them locally, offsite, or in cloud storage, and choose between hot and cold backups depending on availability requirements."

